## 2. The proven IDENTITY — the cross-fixture invariant **[ANALYTIC]**

```
F   = (1/ln2) ln w
F'  = (1/ln2)(w'/w)
S2  = F'' = (1/ln2)(w''/w − (w'/w)²) = (1/ln2)(w·w'' − (w')²)/w²
```

Substituting `w = y²`, `w' = 2yy'`, `w'' = 2y'² + 2yy''`:

```
w''/w − (w'/w)²  =  2(y''/y − (y'/y)²)
⇒  S2  =  (2/ln2)(y''/y − (y'/y)²)  ≡  G2.
```

This is an **identity**, true row-by-row in every fixture by construction — *not* a test that
could have failed. `G2` is the same closed-form differential operator of the operand jet
everywhere; what differs across fixtures is only the **path** `(w, w', w'')(t)` each one traces,
because each has a different `x_term(t)`. **The cross-fixture invariant is the operator `G2`
itself.** Calling this a "PASS" of a verdict cell would be dressing a tautology as a finding —
the trap the prereg's §B "metrology→verdict" promotion would have walked into, caught before
freeze.

**Receipt (the only empirical claim about the identity), [EMPIRICAL]:** finite-differencing
`F(t)` directly (central differences, relative ladder `{1e-2…1e-5}`, plateau-stability gate) and
comparing to `G2` evaluated on the table's own `(y, y', y'')` reproduces the identity to:

| fixture | n (resolved) | max rel-resid | tol | pass |
